# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: detonation-flame-arrester
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] In chemistry, a **substance** is a unique form of matter with constant chemical composition and characteristic properties.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Chemical substances may take the form of a single element or chemical compounds.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] If two or more chemical substances can be combined without reacting, they may form a chemical mixture.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] If a mixture is separated to isolate one chemical substance to a desired degree, the resulting substance is said to be chemically pure.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Chemical substances can exist in several different physical states or phases (e.g. solids, liquids, gases, or plasma) without changing their chemical composition.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Substances transition between these phases of matter in response to changes in temperature or pressure.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Some chemical substances can be combined or converted into new substances by means of chemical reactions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Chemicals that do not possess this ability are said to be inert.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Pure water is an example of a chemical substance, with a constant composition of two hydrogen atoms bonded to a single oxygen atom (i.e.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The atomic ratio of hydrogen to oxygen is always 2:1 in every molecule of water.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Pure water will tend to boil near 100 °C (212 °F), an example of one of the characteristic properties that define it.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Other notable chemical substances include diamond (a form of the element carbon), table salt (NaCl; an ionic compound), and refined sugar (C12H22O11; an organic compound).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] In addition to the generic definition offered above, there are several niche fields where the term "chemical substance" may take alternate usages that are widely accepted, some of which are outlined in the sections below.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Chemical Abstracts Service (CAS) lists several alloys of uncertain composition within their chemical substance index.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] While an alloy could be more closely defined as a mixture, referencing them in the chemical substances index allows CAS to offer specific guidance on standard naming of alloy compositions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Non-stoichiometric compounds are another special case from inorganic chemistry, which violate the requirement for constant composition.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] For these substances, it may be difficult to draw the line between a mixture and a compound, as in the case of palladium hydride.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] In the field of geology, inorganic solid substances of uniform composition are known as minerals.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] When two or more minerals are combined to form mixtures (or aggregates), they are defined as rocks.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Many minerals, however, mutually dissolve into solid solutions, such that a single rock is a uniform substance despite being a mixture in stoichiometric terms.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Feldspars are a common example: anorthoclase is an alkali aluminum silicate, where the alkali metal is interchangeably either sodium or potassium.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] In law, "chemical substances" may include both pure substances and mixtures with a defined composition or manufacturing process.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] For example, the EU regulation REACH defines "monoconstituent substances", "multiconstituent substances" and "substances of unknown or variable composition".
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The latter two consist of multiple chemical substances; however, their identity can be established either by direct chemical analysis or reference to a single manufacturing process.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] For example, charcoal is an extremely complex, partially polymeric mixture that can be defined by its manufacturing process.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Therefore, although the exact chemical identity is unknown, identification can be made with a sufficient accuracy.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The CAS Registry also includes mixtures.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Polymers almost always appear as mixtures of molecules of multiple molar masses, each of which could be considered a separate chemical substance.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] However, the polymer may be defined by a known precursor or reaction(s) and the molar mass distribution.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] For example, polyethylene is a mixture of very long chains of -CH2- repeating units, and is generally sold in several molar mass distributions, LDPE, MDPE, HDPE and UHMWPE.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The concept of a "chemical substance" became firmly established in the late eighteenth century after work by the chemist Joseph Proust on the composition of some pure chemical compounds such as basic copper carbonate.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] He deduced that, "All samples of a compound have the same composition; that is, all samples have the same proportions, by mass, of the elements present in the compound." This is now known as the law of constant composition.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] However, there are some controversies regarding this definition mainly because the large number of chemical substances reported in chemistry literature need to be indexed.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Isomerism caused much consternation to early researchers, since isomers have exactly the same composition, but differ in configuration (arrangement) of the atoms.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] For example, there was much speculation about the chemical identity of benzene, until the correct structure was described by Friedrich August Kekulé.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Likewise, the idea of stereoisomerism – that atoms have rigid three-dimensional structure and can thus form isomers that differ only in their three-dimensional arrangement – was another crucial step in understanding the concept of distinct chemical substances.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] For example, tartaric acid has three distinct isomers, a pair of diastereomers with one diastereomer forming two enantiomers.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] An element is a chemical substance made up of a particular kind of atom and hence cannot be broken down or transformed by a chemical reaction into a different element, though it can be transmuted into another element through a nuclear reaction.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] This is because all of the atoms in a sample of an element have the same number of protons, though they may be different isotopes, with differing numbers of neutrons.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] As of 2025, there are 118 known elements, about 80 of which are stable – that is, they do not change by radioactive decay into other elements.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Some elements can occur as more than a single chemical substance (allotropes).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] For instance, oxygen exists as both diatomic oxygen (O2) and ozone (O3).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The majority of elements are classified as metals.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] These are elements with a characteristic lustre such as iron, copper, and gold.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Metals typically conduct electricity and heat well, and they are malleable and ductile.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Around 14 to 21 elements, such as carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen, are classified as non-metals.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Non-metals lack the metallic properties described above, they also have a high electronegativity and a tendency to form negative ions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Certain elements such as silicon sometimes resemble metals and sometimes resemble non-metals, and are known as metalloids.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] A chemical compound is a chemical substance that is composed of a particular set of atoms or ions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Two or more elements combined into one substance through a chemical reaction form a chemical compound.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] All compounds are substances, but not all substances are compounds.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] A chemical compound can be atoms bonded together in molecules, or in crystals in which atoms, molecules or ions form a crystalline lattice.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Compounds based primarily on carbon and hydrogen atoms are called organic compounds, and all others are called inorganic compounds.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Compounds containing bonds between carbon and a metal are called organometallic compounds.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Compounds in which components share electrons are known as covalent compounds.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Compounds consisting of oppositely charged ions are known as ionic compounds, or salts.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Coordination complexes are compounds where a dative bond keeps the substance together without a covalent or ionic bond.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Coordination complexes are distinct substances with distinct properties different from a simple mixture.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Typically these have a metal, such as a copper ion, in the center, and a non-metal atom, such as the nitrogen in an ammonia molecule or oxygen in a water molecule, forms a dative bond to the metal center, e.g. tetraamminecopper(II) sulfate [Cu(NH3)4]SO4·H2O.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The metal is known as a "metal center" and the substance that coordinates to the center is called a "ligand".
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] However, the center does not need to be a metal, as exemplified by boron trifluoride etherate BF3OEt2, where the highly Lewis acidic, but non-metallic boron center takes the role of the "metal".
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] If the ligand bonds to the metal center with multiple atoms, the complex is called a chelate.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] In organic chemistry, there can be more than one chemical compound with the same composition and molecular weight.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Isomers usually have substantially different chemical properties, and often may be isolated without spontaneously interconverting.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] A common example is glucose vs. fructose.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The former is an aldehyde, the latter is a ketone.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Their interconversion requires either enzymatic or acid-base catalysis.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] However, tautomers are an exception: the isomerization occurs spontaneously in ordinary conditions, such that a pure substance cannot be isolated into its tautomers, even if these can be identified spectroscopically or even isolated in special conditions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] A common example is glucose, which has open-chain and ring forms.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] One cannot manufacture pure open-chain glucose because glucose spontaneously cyclizes to the hemiacetal form.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] All matter consists of various elements and chemical compounds, but these are often intimately mixed together.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Mixtures contain more than one chemical substance, and they do not have a fixed composition.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Butter, soil and wood are common examples of mixtures.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Sometimes, mixtures can be separated into their component substances by mechanical processes, such as chromatography, distillation, or evaporation.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Grey iron metal and yellow sulfur are both chemical elements, and they can be mixed together in any ratio to form a yellow-grey mixture.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] No chemical process occurs, and the material can be identified as a mixture by the fact that the sulfur and the iron can be separated by a mechanical process, such as using a magnet to attract the iron away from the sulfur.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The resulting compound has all the properties of a chemical substance and is not a mixture.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Iron(II) sulfide has its own distinct properties such as melting point and solubility, and the two elements cannot be separated using normal mechanical processes; a magnet will be unable to recover the iron, since there is no metallic iron present in the compound.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] In other words, the chemical substances of which fruits and vegetables, for example, are naturally composed even when growing wild are not called "chemicals" in general usage.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] In countries that require a list of ingredients in products, the "chemicals" listed are industrially produced "chemical substances".
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The word "chemical" is also often used to refer to addictive, narcotic, or mind-altering drugs.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The cause of the difference in production volume is the complexity of the molecular structure of the chemical.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Bulk chemicals are usually much less complex.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] While fine chemicals may be more complex, many of them are simple enough to be sold as "building blocks" in the synthesis of more complex molecules targeted for single use, as named above.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The *production* of a chemical includes not only its synthesis but also its purification to eliminate by-products, impurities, and unreacted starting material involved in the synthesis.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The last step in production should be the analysis of batch lots of chemicals in order to identify and quantify the percentages of impurities for the buyer of the chemicals.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The required purity and analysis depends on the application, but higher tolerance of impurities is usually expected in the production of bulk chemicals.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Thus, the user of the chemical in the US might choose between the bulk or "technical grade" with higher amounts of impurities or a much purer "pharmaceutical grade" (labeled "USP", United States Pharmacopeia).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] "Chemicals" in the commercial and legal sense may also include mixtures of highly variable composition, as they are products made to a technical specification instead of particular chemical substances.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] For example, gasoline is not a single chemical compound or even a particular mixture: different gasolines can have very different chemical compositions, as "gasoline" is primarily defined through source, properties and octane rating.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Every chemical substance has one or more systematic names, usually named according to the IUPAC rules for naming.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] An alternative system is used by the Chemical Abstracts Service (CAS).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Many compounds are also known by their more common, simpler names, many of which predate the systematic name.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] For example, the long-known sugar glucose is now systematically named 6-(hydroxymethyl)oxane-2,3,4,5-tetrol.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Natural products and pharmaceuticals are also given simpler names, for example the mild pain-killer Naproxen is the more common name for the chemical compound (S)-6-methoxy-α-methyl-2-naphthaleneacetic acid.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Chemists frequently refer to chemical compounds using chemical formulae or molecular structure of the compound.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] There has been a phenomenal growth in the number of chemical compounds being synthesized (or isolated), and then reported in the scientific literature by professional chemists around the world.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] An enormous number of chemical compounds are possible through the chemical combination of the known chemical elements.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] As of Feb 2021, about "177 million organic and inorganic substances" (including 68 million defined-sequence biopolymers) are in the scientific literature and registered in public databases.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The names of many of these compounds are often nontrivial and hence not very easy to remember or cite accurately.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Also, it is difficult to keep track of them in the literature.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Several international organizations like IUPAC and CAS have initiated steps to make such tasks easier.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] CAS provides the abstracting services of the chemical literature, and provides a numerical identifier, known as CAS registry number to each chemical substance that has been reported in the chemical literature (such as chemistry journals and patents).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] This information is compiled as a database and is popularly known as the Chemical substances index.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Other computer-friendly systems that have been developed for substance information are: SMILES and the International Chemical Identifier or InChI.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Often a pure substance needs to be isolated from a mixture, for example from a natural source (where a sample often contains numerous chemical substances) or after a chemical reaction (which often gives mixtures of chemical substances).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Stoichiometry (/ˌstɔɪkiˈɒmɪtri/ ⓘ) is the relationships between the quantities of reactants and products before, during and after chemical reactions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Stoichiometry is based on the law of conservation of mass; the total mass of reactants must equal the total mass of products, so the relationship between reactants and products must form a ratio of positive integers.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] This means that if the amounts of the separate reactants are known, then the amount of the product can be calculated.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Conversely, if one reactant has a known quantity and the quantity of the products can be empirically determined, then the amount of the other reactants can also be calculated.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] However, the current equation is imbalanced.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The reactants have 4 hydrogen and 2 oxygen atoms, while the product has 2 hydrogen and 3 oxygen.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Here, one molecule of methane reacts with two molecules of oxygen gas to yield one molecule of carbon dioxide and two molecules of liquid water.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] This particular chemical equation is an example of complete combustion.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] The numbers in front of each quantity are a set of stoichiometric coefficients which directly reflect the molar ratios between the products and reactants.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Stoichiometry measures these quantitative relationships, and is used to determine the amount of products and reactants that are produced or needed in a given reaction.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Describing the quantitative relationships among substances as they participate in chemical reactions is known as *reaction stoichiometry*.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] Because of the well-known relationship of moles to atomic weights, the ratios that are arrived at by stoichiometry can be used to determine quantities by weight in a reaction described by a balanced equation.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/chemical] This is called *composition stoichiometry*.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The **Clean Air Act** (**CAA**) is the United States' primary federal air quality law, intended to reduce and control air pollution nationwide.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Initially enacted in 1963 and amended many times since, it is one of the United States' first and most influential modern environmental laws.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] As with many other major U.S. federal environmental statutes, the Clean Air Act is administered by the U.S.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), in coordination with state, local, and tribal governments.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA develops extensive administrative regulations to carry out the law's mandates.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Associated regulatory programs, which are often technical and complex, implement these regulations.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Other programs create requirements for vehicle fuels, industrial facilities, and other technologies and activities that impact air quality.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Newer programs tackle specific problems, including acid rain, ozone layer protection, and climate change.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The CAA has been challenged in court many times, both by environmental groups seeking more stringent enforcement and by states and utilities seeking greater leeway in regulation.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Although its exact benefits depend on what is counted, the Clean Air Act has substantially reduced air pollution and improved US air quality—benefits which EPA credits with saving trillions of dollars and many thousands of lives each year.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In the United States, the "Clean Air Act" typically refers to the codified statute at 42 U.S.C. ch.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] That statute is the product of multiple acts of Congress, one of which—the 1963 act—was actually titled the Clean Air Act, and another of which—the 1970 act—is most often referred to as such.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Code, the statute itself is divided into subchapters, and the section numbers are not clearly related to the subchapters.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] However, in the bills that created the law, the major divisions are called "Titles", and the law's sections are numbered according to the title (e.g., Title II begins with Section 201).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In practice, EPA, courts, and attorneys often use the latter numbering scheme.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Although many parts of the statute are quite detailed, others set out only the general outlines of the law's regulatory programs, and leave many key terms undefined.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Responsible agencies, primarily EPA, have therefore developed administrative regulations to carry out Congress's instructions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA's proposed and final regulations are published in the Federal Register, often with lengthy background histories.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The existing CAA regulations are codified at 40 C.F.R.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] These Parts more often correspond to the Clean Air Act's major regulatory programs.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The following are major regulatory programs under the Clean Air Act.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The National Ambient Air Quality Standards (NAAQS) govern how much ground-level ozone (O3), carbon monoxide (CO), particulate matter (PM10, PM2.5), lead (Pb), sulfur dioxide (SO2), and nitrogen dioxide (NO2) are allowed in the outdoor air.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The NAAQS set the acceptable levels of certain air pollutants in the ambient air in the United States.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Prior to 1965, there was no national program for developing ambient air quality standards, and prior to 1970 the federal government did not have primary responsibility for developing them.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1970 CAA amendments required EPA to determine which air pollutants posed the greatest threat to public health and welfare and promulgate NAAQS and air quality criteria for them.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The health-based standards were called "primary" NAAQS, while standards set to protect public welfare other than health (e.g., agricultural values) were called "secondary" NAAQS.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In 1971, EPA promulgated regulations for sulfur oxides, particulate matter, carbon monoxide, photochemical oxidants, hydrocarbons, and nitrogen dioxide (36 FR 22384).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Initially, EPA did not list lead as a criteria air pollutant, controlling it through mobile source authorities, but it was required to do so after successful litigation by Natural Resources Defense Council (NRDC) in 1976 (43 FR 46258).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1977 CAA Amendments created a process for regular review of the NAAQS list, and created a permanent independent scientific review committee to provide technical input on the NAAQS to EPA.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA added regulations for PM2.5 in 1997 and updates the NAAQS from time to time based on emerging environmental and health science.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The National Emissions Standards for Hazardous Air Pollutants (NESHAPs) govern how much of 187 toxic air pollutants are allowed to be emitted from industrial facilities and other sources.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] These pollutants are often referred to as "air toxics" and include chemicals that are known or suspected to cause cancer, birth defects, and other serious health issues.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Under the CAA, hazardous air pollutants (HAPs, or air toxics) are air pollutants other than those for which NAAQS exist, which threaten human health and welfare.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The NESHAPs are the standards used for controlling, reducing, and eliminating HAPs emissions from stationary sources such as industrial facilities.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1970 CAA required EPA to develop a list of HAPs, and then develop national emissions standards for each of them.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The original NESHAPs were health-based standards.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] 101–549 Title III) codified EPA's list, and required creation of technology-based standards according to "maximum achievable control technology" (MACT).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Over the years, EPA has issued dozens of NESHAP regulations, which have developed NESHAPs by pollutant, by industry source category, and by industrial process.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] There are also NESHAPs for mobile sources (transportation), although these are primarily handled under the mobile source authorities.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1990 amendments (adding CAA § 112(d-f)) also created a process by which EPA was required to review and update its NESHAPs every eight years, and identify any risks remaining after application of MACT, and develop additional rules necessary to protect public health.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The New Source Performance Standards (NSPS) are rules for the equipment required to be installed in new and modified industrial facilities, and the rules for determining whether a facility is "new".
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Since then, EPA has issued dozens of NSPS regulations, primarily by source category.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The requirements promote industrywide adoption of available pollution control technologies.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] However, because these standards apply only to new and modified sources, they promote extending the lifetimes of pre-existing facilities.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In the 1977 CAA Amendments, Congress required EPA to conduct a "new source review" process (40 CFR 52, subpart I) to determine whether maintenance and other activities rises to the level of modification requiring application of NSPS.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Acid Rain Program (ARP) is an emissions trading program for power plants to control the pollutants that cause acid rain.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1990 CAA Amendments created a new title to address the issue of acid rain, and particularly nitrogen oxides (NOx) and sulfur dioxide (SO2) emissions from electric power plants powered by fossil fuels, and other industrial sources.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Acid Rain Program (ARP), established under the 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments, was the first cap-and-trade emissions program in the United States, aimed at reducing sulfur dioxide (SO2) and nitrogen oxides (NOx) emissions, the primary contributors to acid rain.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The program set a national cap on total emissions of SO2 and NOx from power plants, which was gradually reduced over time.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Power plants were allocated emission allowances, each allowing the release of one ton of SO2, based on historical emissions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Plants that reduced their emissions below their allowances could trade excess allowances with other plants, creating a financial incentive to invest in cleaner technologies.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Continuous emissions monitoring systems were required to ensure compliance, and plants that exceeded their allowances faced fines.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The program's success is evident in the 50% reduction of SO2 emissions from power plants by 2000, significantly improving air quality and reducing acid rain.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Acid Rain Program became a model for subsequent cap-and-trade systems, including those targeting greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The CAA ozone program is a technology transition program intended to phase out the use of chemicals that harm the ozone layer.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Consistent with the US commitments in the Montreal Protocol, CAA Title VI, added by the 1990 CAA Amendments, mandated regulations regarding the use and production of chemicals that harm Earth's stratospheric ozone layer.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Ozone-depleting chemicals (ODCs) are substances that contribute to the depletion of Earth's stratospheric ozone layer, which protects life on Earth from harmful ultraviolet (UV) radiation.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The primary ODCs regulated under the Clean Air Act (CAA) and the Montreal Protocol include chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs), halons, hydrochlorofluorocarbons (HCFCs), hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs), methyl chloroform, and carbon tetrachloride.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] CFCs were commonly used in refrigeration, air conditioning, and foam-blowing agents, while halons were used in fire extinguishing systems.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] HCFCs were seen as less harmful alternatives to CFCs but still contributed to ozone depletion, and they are also being phased out.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Rules for pollutants emitted from internal combustion engines in vehicles.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Since 1965, Congress has mandated increasingly stringent controls on vehicle engine technology and reductions in tailpipe emissions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Mobile source pollutants are emissions produced by internal combustion engines in motor vehicles, including cars, trucks, and buses.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA has set increasingly stringent controls on these emissions from motor vehicles, aiming to reduce their impact on public health and the environment by incorporating advanced engine technologies that balance emission reductions with factors such as cost, energy use, and safety.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Since the introduction of vehicle emissions regulations in 1965 and the subsequent amendments to the Clean Air Act (CAA), significant reductions in mobile source pollutants have been achieved.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Carbon monoxide (CO) emissions have decreased by more than 80% since 1970, primarily due to improvements in engine design and the introduction of catalytic converters.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Nitrogen oxides (NOx) emissions have been reduced by over 50% since 1970, driven by advancements in engine technology and stricter emission standards.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Particulate matter (PM) emissions have dropped by more than 90%, thanks to cleaner-burning engines and the use of diesel particulate filters.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Volatile organic compounds (VOCs) have been reduced by around 85% since 1970, due to better fuel management and evaporative emission controls.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Hydrocarbon (HC) emissions have decreased by approximately 80%, facilitated by improvements in fuel combustion technology and engine control strategies.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] While carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions per mile have been reduced by 30-40% since the 1970s due to increased fuel efficiency, total CO2 emissions remain a concern due to increased vehicle miles traveled and the growth of larger vehicles.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] These reductions are the result of technological advancements, such as catalytic converters, on-board diagnostics, and more efficient engines, along with stricter fuel standards and the use of alternative fuels.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The EPA continues to update and enforce emission standards to further reduce the impact of vehicle emissions on air quality and public health.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA sets standards for exhaust gases, evaporative emissions, air toxics, refueling vapor recovery, and vehicle inspection and maintenance for several classes of vehicles that travel on roadways.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA's "light-duty vehicles" regulations cover passenger cars, minivans, passenger vans, pickup trucks, and SUVs.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] "Heavy-duty vehicles" regulations cover large trucks and buses.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA first issued motorcycle emissions regulations in 1977 (42 FR 1122) and updated them in 2004 (69 FR 2397).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The air pollution testing system for motor vehicles was originally developed in 1972 and used driving cycles designed to simulate driving during rush-hour in Los Angeles during that era.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Until 1984, EPA reported the exact fuel economy figures calculated from the test.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In 1996, EPA proposed updating the Federal Testing Procedures to add a new higher-speed test (US06) and an air-conditioner-on test (SC03) to further improve the correlation of fuel economy and emission estimates with real-world reports.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In December 2006 the updated testing methodology was finalized to be implemented in model year 2008 vehicles and set the precedent of a 12-year review cycle for the test procedures.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In February 2005, EPA launched a program called "Your MPG" that allows drivers to add real-world fuel economy statistics into a database on EPA's fuel economy website and compare them with others and with the original EPA test results.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA conducts fuel economy tests on very few vehicles.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Two-thirds of the vehicles the EPA tests themselves are randomly selected and the remaining third is tested for specific reasons.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Although originally created as a reference point for fossil-fueled vehicles, driving cycles have been used for estimating how many miles an electric vehicle will get on a single charge.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1970 CAA amendments provided for regulation of aircraft emissions (42 U.S.C. § 7571), and EPA began regulating in 1973.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In 2012, EPA finalized its newest restrictions on NOx emissions from gas turbine aircraft engines with rated thrusts above 26.7 kiloNewton (3 short ton-force), meaning primarily commercial jet aircraft engines, intended to match international standards.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA has been investigating whether to regulate lead in fuels for small aircraft since 2010, but has not yet acted.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] 101–549 § 222) added rules for a "nonroad" engine program (42 U.S.C. § 7547), which expanded EPA regulation to locomotives, heavy equipment and small equipment engines fueled by diesel (compression-ignition), and gas and other fuels (spark-ignition), and marine transport.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA has developed a variety of voluntary programs to incentivize and promote reduction in transportation-related air pollution, including elements of the Clean Diesel Campaign, Ports Initiative, "SmartWay" program (for the freight transportation sector), and others.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The federal government has regulated the chemical composition of transportation fuels since 1967, with significant new authority added in 1970 to protect public health.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1990 amendments authorized a national operating permit program, sometimes called the "Title V Program", covering thousands of large industrial and commercial sources.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] It required large businesses to address pollutants released into the air, measure their quantity, and have a plan to control and minimize them as well as to periodically report.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] This consolidated requirements for a facility into a single document.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In non-attainment areas, permits were required for sources that emit as little as 50, 25, or 10 tons per year of VOCs depending on the severity of the region's non-attainment status.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Most permits are issued by state and local agencies.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] If the state does not adequately monitor requirements, the EPA may take control.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The public may request to view the permits by contacting the EPA.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The permit is limited to no more than five years and requires a renewal.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Pursuant to one of the most public aspects of the Clean Air Act, EPA is empowered to monitor compliance with the law's many requirements, seek penalties for violations, and compel regulated entities to come into compliance.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Enforcement cases are usually settled, with penalties assessed well below maximum statutory limits.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Many of the largest Clean Air Act settlements have been reached with automakers accused of circumventing the Act's vehicle and fuel standards (e.g., the 2015 "Dieselgate" scandal).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Much of EPA's regulation of greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions occurs under the programs discussed above.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA began regulating GHG emissions following the 2007 Supreme Court ruling in *Massachusetts v.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA*, the EPA's subsequent endangerment finding, and development of specific regulations for various sources.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The EPA's authority to regulate carbon dioxide emissions was questioned by the court in *West Virginia v.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA* (2022) but restored by Congress with the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022, which clarified that carbon dioxide is one of the pollutants covered by the Clean Air Act.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Standards for mobile sources have been established pursuant to Section 202 of the CAA, and GHGs from stationary sources are controlled under the authority of Part C of Title I of the Act.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The EPA's auto emission standards for greenhouse gas emissions issued in 2010 and 2012 are intended to cut emissions from targeted vehicles by half, double fuel economy of passenger cars and light-duty trucks by 2025 and save over $4 billion barrels of oil and $1.7 trillion for consumers.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The agency has also proposed a two-phase program to reduce greenhouse gas emissions for medium and heavy duty trucks and buses.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In addition, EPA oversees the national greenhouse gas inventory reporting program.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Following the Supreme Court decision in *West Virginia v.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1963 act required development of State Implementation Plans (SIPs) as part of a cooperative federalist program for developing pollution control standards and programs.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Rather than create a solely national program, the CAA imposes responsibilities on the U.S. states to create plans to implement the Act's requirements.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA then reviews, amends, and approves those plans.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA first promulgated SIP regulations in 1971 and 1972.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1970 Amendments imposed eight criteria that an implementation plan must meet.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The EPA is required to approve plans that adhere to the Senate's three-year mandate for primary air quality standards even if the Agency feels the plan does not appear feasible.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Environmental Protection Agency* the Supreme Court considered whether the Agency was required to reject plans that were not technologically or economically feasible.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The court decided that states could adopt emission standards stricter than national standards and "force" technology (i.e. require installation of more advanced technologies).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1977 CAA Amendments added SIP requirements for areas that had not attained the applicable NAAQS ("nonattainment areas").
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In these areas, states were required to adopt plans that made "reasonable further progress" toward attainment until all "reasonably available control measures" could be adopted.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] As progress on attainment was much slower than Congress originally instructed, major amendments to SIP requirements in nonattainment areas were part of the 1990 CAA Amendments.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1977 CAA Amendments modified the SIP requirements by adding "Prevention of Significant Deterioration" (PSD) requirements.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] These requirements protect areas, including particularly wilderness areas and national parks, that already met the NAAQS.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The PSD provision requires SIPs to preserve good quality air in addition to cleaning up bad air.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The new law also required New Source Review (investigations of proposed construction of new polluting facilities) to examine whether PSD requirements would be met.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Clean Air Act provided the EPA with enforcement authority and requiring states to develop State Implementation Plans for how they would meet new national ambient air quality standards by 1977.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] This cooperative federal model continues today.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The law recognizes that states should lead in carrying out the Clean Air Act, because pollution control problems often require special understanding of local conditions such as geography, industrial activity, transportation and housing patterns.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] However, states are not allowed to have weaker controls than the national minimum criteria set by EPA.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA must approve each SIP, and if a SIP is not acceptable, EPA can retain CAA enforcement in that state.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] For example, California was unable to meet the new standards set by the 1970 amendments, which led to a lawsuit and a federal state implementation plan for the state.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The federal government also assists the states by providing scientific research, expert studies, engineering designs, and money to support clean air programs.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The law also prevents states from setting standards that are more strict than the federal standards, but carves out a special exemption for California due to its past issues with smog pollution in the metropolitan areas.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In practice, when California's environmental agencies decide on new vehicle emission standards, they are submitted to the EPA for approval under this waiver, with the most recent approval in 2009.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The California standard was adopted by twelve other states, and established the *de facto* standard that automobile manufacturers subsequently accepted, to avoid having to develop different emission systems in their vehicles for different states.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] However, in September 2019, President Donald Trump attempted to revoke this waiver, arguing that the stricter emissions have made cars too expensive, and by removing them, will make vehicles safer.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA's Andrew Wheeler also stated that while the agency respects federalism, it could not allow one state to dictate standards for the entire nation.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] California's governor Gavin Newsom considered the move part of Trump's "political vendetta" against California and stated his intent to sue the federal government.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Twenty-three states, along with the District of Columbia and the cities of New York City and Los Angeles, joined California in a federal lawsuit challenging the administration's decision.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In March 2022 the Biden administration reversed the Trump-era rule, allowing California to again set stricter auto emissions standards.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Between the Second Industrial Revolution and the 1960s, the United States experienced increasingly severe air pollution.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Following the 1948 Donora smog event, the public began to discuss air pollution as a major problem, states began to pass a series of laws to reduce air pollution, and Congress began discussing whether to take further action in response.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] After several years of proposals and hearings, Congress passed the first federal legislation to address air pollution in 1955.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Air Pollution Control Act of 1955 authorized a research and training program, sending $3 million per year to the U.S.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Public Health Service for five years, but did not directly regulate pollution sources.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1955 Act's research program was extended in 1959, 1960, and 1962 while Congress considered whether to regulate further.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Beginning in 1963, Congress began expanding federal air pollution control law to accelerate the elimination of air pollution throughout the country.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The new law's programs were initially administered by the U.S.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Secretary of Health, Education, and Welfare, and the Air Pollution Office of the U.S.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Public Health Service, until they were transferred to the newly created EPA immediately before major amendments in 1970.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA has administered the Clean Air Act ever since, and Congress added major regulatory programs in 1977 and 1990.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Supreme Court's ruling in *Massachusetts v.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA* resulted in an expansion of EPA's CAA regulatory activities to cover greenhouse gases.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] 88–206) was the first federal legislation to permit the U.S. federal government to take direct action to control air pollution.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Motor Vehicle Air Pollution Control Act (Pub.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] 89–272) amended the 1963 Clean Air Act and set the first federal vehicle emissions standards, beginning with the 1968 models.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] These standards were reductions from 1963 emissions levels: 72% reduction for hydrocarbons, 56% reduction for carbon monoxide, and 100% reduction for crankcase hydrocarbons..
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The law also added a new section to authorize abatement of international air pollution.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] It also authorized expanded studies of air pollutant emission inventories, ambient monitoring techniques, and control techniques.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] This enabled the federal government to increase its activities to investigate enforcing interstate air pollution transport, and, for the first time, to perform far-reaching ambient monitoring studies and stationary source inspections.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1967 act also authorized expanded studies of air pollutant emission inventories, ambient monitoring techniques, and control techniques.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] While only six states had air pollution programs in 1960, all 50 states had air pollution programs by 1970 due to the federal funding and legislation of the 1960s.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In the Clean Air Amendments of 1970 congress greatly expanded the federal mandate by requiring comprehensive federal and state regulations for both industrial and mobile sources.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] To implement the strict amendments, EPA Administrator William Ruckelshaus spent 60% of his time during his first term on the automobile industry, whose emissions were to be reduced 90% under the new law.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Senators had been frustrated at the industry's failure to cut emissions under previous, weaker air laws.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Major amendments were added to the *Clean Air Act* in 1977 (1977 CAAA).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1977 Amendments primarily concerned provisions for the Prevention of Significant Deterioration (PSD) of air quality in areas attaining the NAAQS.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1977 CAAA also contained requirements pertaining to sources in non-attainment areas for NAAQS.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] A non-attainment area is a geographic area that does not meet one or more of the federal air quality standards.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Both of these 1977 CAAA established major permit review requirements to ensure attainment and maintenance of the NAAQS.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] These amendments also included the adoption of an offset trading policy originally applied to Los Angeles in 1974 that enables new sources to offset their emissions by purchasing extra reductions from existing sources.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Another set of major amendments to the Clean Air Act occurred in 1990 (1990 CAAA) (104 Stat.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1990 CAAA substantially increased the authority and responsibility of the federal government.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] New regulatory programs were authorized for control of acid deposition (acid rain) and for the issuance of stationary source operating permits.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The NESHAPs were incorporated into a greatly expanded program for controlling toxic air pollutants.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The provisions for attainment and maintenance of NAAQS were substantially modified and expanded.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Other revisions included provisions regarding stratospheric ozone protection, increased enforcement authority, and expanded research programs.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1990 Clean Air Act added regulatory programs for control of acid deposition (acid rain) and stationary source operating permits.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The provisions aimed at reducing sulfur dioxide emissions included a cap-and-trade program, which gave power companies more flexibility in meeting the law's goals compared to earlier iterations of the Clean Air Act.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The amendments moved considerably beyond the original criteria pollutants, expanding the NESHAP program with a list of 189 hazardous air pollutants to be controlled within hundreds of source categories, according to a specific schedule.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Other new provisions covered stratospheric ozone protection, increased enforcement authority and expanded research programs.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Further amendments were made in 1990 to address the problems of acid rain, ozone depletion, and toxic air pollution, and to establish a national permit program for stationary sources, and increased enforcement authority.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The amendments also established new auto gasoline reformulation requirements, set Reid vapor pressure (RVP) standards to control evaporative emissions from gasoline, and mandated new gasoline formulations sold from May to September in many states.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Reviewing his tenure as EPA Administrator under President George H.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Reilly characterized passage of the 1990 amendments to the Clean Air Act as his most notable accomplishment.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The 1990 amendments also included a requirement for the Department of Labor to issue, no later than 12 months from the date of publication of the amendments, and in collaboration with the EPA, a "process safety standard".
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The text also highlighted the 14 principles on which this should be based.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] These were implemented in 1992 in OSHA's Process Safety Management regulation (Title 29 CFR Part 1910, Subpart H § 1910.119), as well as in EPA's 1996 Risk Management Program (RMP) rule (Title 40 CFR Part 68).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Inflation Reduction Act, the budget reconciliation bill signed by President Joe Biden in August 2022, amends the Clean Air Act to allow the EPA to administer $27 billion in grants to green banks nationwide, through a competitive funding mechanism to be called the Greenhouse Gas Reduction Fund.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] On April 4, 2024, the Biden administration announced the eight recipients of the first $20 billion of the Greenhouse Gas Reduction Fund.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Biden administration projects that they will leverage $7 from the private sector for every dollar of public investment, and slash emissions by up to 40 million metric tons by 2032 through a wide variety of projects.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The remaining $7 billion will go to 60 distributed generation projects in low-income communities, and is forecast to collectively save 900,000 households $8 billion in energy bills by the IRA's expiration.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Act is expected to generate high rates of return for the government on private sector investments from the Fund.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Act also designates carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases as substances to be regulated by the EPA, in reaction to the Supreme Court case *West Virginia v.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] EPA*, which limited the EPA's authority to institute a program such as the Obama-era Clean Power Plan.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The IRA also allows the EPA more leeway to promote renewable energy.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] According to a 2022 review study in the *Journal of Economic Literature*, there is overwhelming causal evidence that shows that the CAA improved air quality.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In 2020, a study prepared for the Natural Resources Defense Council estimated annual benefits at 370,000 avoided premature deaths, 189,000 fewer hospital admissions, and net economic benefits of up to $3.8 trillion (32 times the cost of the regulations).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Other studies have reached similar conclusions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Mobile sources including automobiles, trains, and boat engines have become 99% cleaner for pollutants like hydrocarbons, carbon monoxide, nitrogen oxides, and particle emissions since the 1970s.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The allowable emissions of volatile organic chemicals, carbon monoxide, nitrogen oxides, and lead from individual cars have also been reduced by more than 90%, resulting in decreased national emissions of these pollutants despite a more than 400% increase in total miles driven yearly.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Since the 1980s, 1/4th of ground level ozone has been cut, mercury emissions have been cut by 80%, and since the change from leaded gas to unleaded gas 90% of atmospheric lead pollution has been reduced.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] A 2018 study found that the Clean Air Act contributed to the 60% decline in pollution emissions by the manufacturing industry between 1990 and 2008.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Since its inception, the authority given to the EPA by Congress and the EPA's rulemaking within the Clean Air Act has been subject to numerous lawsuits.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Under the Clean Air Act, states were required to submit their implementation plans within nine months of the EPA's promulgation of the new standards.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The EPA approved several state plans that allowed for variances in their emissions limitations, and the Natural Resources Defense Council challenged that approval.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Clean Air Act instructed the EPA to regulate emissions from sources of air pollution, but did not define what should be considered a source for the emission of air pollution, so the EPA had interpreted what a source was based on the legislation.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] to establish their own interpretation of law when the law is ambiguous and the interpretation is reasonable and consistent.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] applying to any executive agency granted powers from Congress.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] found in favor of the trucking industry, determining that the EPA's rule did not consider the costs of implementing emissions regulations and controls.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] District Court's ruling, affirming that not only was the delegation of power from Congress to the EPA by the Clean Air Act constitutional, but that the law did not require the EPA to consider costs as part of its determination for air quality controls.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Multiple states and agencies sued the EPA for failing to act on what they considered to be harmful air pollutants.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled 5–4 that not only did the Clean Air Act mandate the EPA to regulate carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases as air pollutants, but that failing to regulate these emissions would leave the EPA liable to further litigation.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] , as it opened up the courts for further environmental lawsuits to force entities to respond to climate change.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The EPA issued new rules in 2010 that expanded emissions regulations for both regulated air pollutants and greenhouse gases to light and heavy engines and smaller stationary sources.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] These expanded rules were challenged by several power companies and regulatory groups, as they greatly expanded what types of facilities would need to acquire environmental permits prior to construction.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court generally upheld the EPA's powers through the Clean Air Act, through it vacated portions of the EPA's new rules affecting smaller sources.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In 2012, the EPA issued new rules that identified new pollutants such as mercury as hazardous materials to be regulated in power plant emissions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The cost of implementing mercury pollution controls on new and existing plants can be expensive, and several states, companies, and other organizations sued the EPA that their analysis leading to these new rules did not consider the cost factor involved.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled 5–4 that the EPA's failure to consider the costs of these pollution controls was inappropriate, and that cost must be a factor in any finding that the EPA finds "necessary and appropriate" under the Clean Air Act.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] (CPP), which aimed to combat climate change by reducing carbon dioxide emissions from coal-burning power plants.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] , the agency sought to regulate emissions from existing power plants.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] After the final plan was announced in 2015, a number of states successfully petitioned federal courts for an emergency stay to block the implementation of the plan.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] In 2017, the CPP never having been implemented, the EPA under the Trump administration enacted the Affordable Clean Energy (ACE) rule, which repealed the CPP.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] A different set of states and environmental advocacy groups challenged the ACE rule in federal court, and on January 19, 2021, the D.C.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] Circuit Court of Appeals vacated the rule because it relied on a flawed interpretation of § 7411(d).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] A number of states petitioned the Supreme Court, arguing that the D.C.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p01] and thus required more specific Congressional approval than could reasonably be argued to be present in the statute.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] As poor air quality is still an issue in the United States, it has been noted that it is 1.5 times more likely for an ethnic minority person to live in an area burdened with air pollution than it is for an ethnic majority person.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] While the United States is still being affected by the COVID-19 pandemic, research has shown that if someone lives in an area that experiences air pollution, they are 8% more likely to experience long-term COVID effects, potentially with a fatal outcome.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] Solutions proposed by the Sierra Club and the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) include funding clean energy transportation services, lowering acceptable emission levels, and enforcing the Clean Air Act that is already in place more intensely.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] While the Clean Air Act has been generally effective since it was enacted in 1970, there have been efforts from the fossil fuel industry to override it which have led to worse air pollution in many communities.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] An example of an area where the Clean Air Act has not been too effective is the San Joaquin Valley which experiences poor air quality conditions that stem from harmful agricultural practices, heavy traffic on major roadways, and the oil industry.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] Research shows that the leading air pollutant in the region is known as PM 2.5, or fine particulate matter, and causes health issues in pregnant women exposed to it, such as more severe asthma, decreased FEV1, compromised immunity, and an increased risk of premature birth.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] Other symptoms that come from exposure to PM 2.5 include chronic bronchitis, reduced lung function in children, and heart and lung-related hospitalizations that can potentially lead to premature death especially if the individual has previous health concerns.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] In 2004, a mass decrease in PM 2.5 pollution occurred because of a decline in agricultural and biomass burning practices; however, it is still a common occurrence today and PM 2.5 levels have increased.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] Organizations such as the California Air Resources Board (CARB) have recommended that more sufficient regulations be implemented in the San Joaquin Valley to reduce toxic emissions into the atmosphere.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] There are now efforts from the EPA, the CARB, and the San Joaquin Valley Air Pollution Control District to enforce regulations from the Clean Air Act and fund further efforts to live in a more sustainable fashion.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] As of 2017, some US cities still do not meet all national ambient air quality standards.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] It is likely that tens of thousands of premature deaths are still being caused by fine-particle pollution and ground-level ozone pollution.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] Climate change poses a challenge to the management of conventional air pollutants in the United States due to warmer, dryer summer conditions that can lead to increased air stagnation episodes.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] Prolonged droughts that may contribute to wildfires would also result in regionally high levels of air particles.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] Transboundary air pollution (both entering and exiting the United States) is not directly regulated by the Clean Air Act, requiring international negotiations and ongoing agreements with other nations, particularly Canada and Mexico.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] Environmental justice continues to be an ongoing challenge for the Clean Air Act.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] By promoting pollution reduction, the Clean Air Act helps reduce heightened exposure to air pollution among minority and low-income communities.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] But African American populations are "consistently over represented" in areas with the poorest air quality.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] Dense populations of low-income and minority communities inhabit the most polluted areas across the United States, which is considered to exacerbate health problems among these populations.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] High levels of exposure to air pollution is linked to several health conditions, including asthma, cancer, premature death, and infant mortality, each of which disproportionately impact minority and low-income communities.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/clean-air-act-united-states-p02] The pollution reduction achieved by the Clean Air Act is associated with a decline in each of these conditions and can promote environmental justice for communities that are disproportionately impacted by air pollution and diminished health status.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] A **detonation flame arrester** (also spelled **arrestor**) is a device fitted to the opening of an enclosure or to the connecting pipe work of a system of enclosures and whose intended function is to allow flow but prevent the transmission of flame propagating at supersonic velocity.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] Detonation Flame Arrester products were created in response to environmental regulations (such as The Clean Air Act) which required liquid product storage terminals and hydrocarbon processing plants to control evaporative hydrocarbon emissions from loading and storage operations.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] Two types of recognized vapor control technologies are commonly used; carbon adsorption vapor recovery and vapor destruction or combustion.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] Vapor destruction systems include elevated flare systems, enclosed flare systems, burner and catalytic incineration systems, and waste gas boilers.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] Both systems require flame or detonation flame arresters to maximize safety.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] Detonation flame arresters are used in many industries, including refining, pharmaceutical, chemical, and petrochemical, pulp and paper, oil exploration and production, sewage treatment, landfills, mining, power generation, and bulk liquids transportation.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] Flame arresters are passive devices with no moving parts.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] They prevent the propagation of flame from the exposed side of the unit to the protected side by the use of metal matrix creating a tortuous path called a flame cell or element.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] Detonation flame arresters made by most manufacturers employ layers of metal ribbons with crimped corrugations.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] The internal narrow passages of the crimped corrugations make up the element matrix.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] These passages are measured as the hydraulic diameter and are made smaller for gases having smaller maximum experimental safe gaps (MESG).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] Under normal operating conditions the flame arrester permits a relatively free flow of gas or vapor through the piping system.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] If the mixture is ignited and the flame begins to travel back through the piping, the arrester will prohibit the flame from moving back to the gas source.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] Most detonation flame arrester applications are in systems which collect gases emitted by liquids and solids.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] These systems, commonly used in many industries, may be called vapor control systems.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] The gases which are vented to atmosphere or controlled via vapor control systems are typically flammable.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] If the conditions are such that ignition occurs, a flame propagation inside or outside of the system could result, with the potential to do catastrophic damage.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] The first patented detonation flame arrester was developed by Nicholas Roussakis et al., U.S. patent 4,909,730 and was issued on March 20, 1990.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] Its need was initially driven by new environmental legislation, namely the Clean Air Act of the USA.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] Regular flame arresters had been around for years, but they had very limited applications.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/detonation-flame-arrester] There have been at least a dozen more since then.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] A **flame arrester** (also spelled **arrestor**), **deflagration arrester**, or **flame trap** is a device or form of construction that allows free passage of gas but will interrupt or prevent the passage of flame.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] It prevents the transmission of flame through a flammable gas/air mixture by quenching the flame on the high surface area provided by an array of small passages through which the flame must pass.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] The emerging gases are cooled enough to prevent ignition on the protected side.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] Flame arresters are safety devices fitted to openings of enclosures or to pipe work, and are intended to allow flow but prevent flame transmission.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] A flame arrester functions by absorbing the heat from a flame front thus dropping the burning gas/air mixture below its auto-ignition temperature; consequently, the flame cannot survive.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] The heat is absorbed through channels (passages) designed into an element.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] These channels are chosen and measured as the MESG (maximum experimental safe gap) of the gas for a particular installation.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] These passages can be regular, like crimped metal ribbon or wire mesh or a sheet metal plate with punched holes, or irregular, such as those in random packing.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] The required size of the channels needed to stop the flame front can vary significantly, depending on the flammability of the fuel mixture.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] The large openings on a chain link fence are capable of slowing the spread of a small, slow-burning grass fire, but fast-burning grass fires will penetrate the fence unless the holes are very small.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] In a coal mine containing highly explosive coal dust or methane, the wire mesh of a Davy lamp must be very tightly spaced.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] For flame arresters used as a safety device, the mesh must be protected from damage due to being dropped or struck by another object, and the mesh must be capable of rigidly retaining its shape during the propagation of a flame front.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] Any shifting of the individual wires that make up the mesh can create an opening large enough to allow the flame to penetrate and spread beyond the barrier.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] On a fuel storage vent, flame arresters also serve a secondary purpose of allowing air pressure to equalize inside the tank when fuel is added or removed, while also preventing insects from flying or crawling into the vent piping and fouling the fuel in the tanks and pipes.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] Flame arresters should be used only in the gas group and conditions they have been designed and tested for.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] Since the depth on an arrester is specified for certain conditions, changes in the temperature, pressure, or composition of the gases entering the arrester can cause the flame spatial velocity to increase, making the design of the arrester insufficient to stop the flame front ("propagation").
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] The deflagration may continue downstream of the arrester.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] Flame arresters should be periodically inspected to make sure they are free of dirt, insects using it as a nest, or corrosion.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flame-arrester] Chemical Safety and Hazard Investigation Board concluded that an uninspected and badly corroded flame arrester failed to prevent a 2006 explosion at a wastewater treatment plant in Daytona Beach, Florida.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] A **flashback arrestor** or flash arrestor is a gas safety device most commonly used in oxy-fuel welding and cutting to stop the flame or reverse flow of gas back up into the equipment or supply line.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] It protects the user and equipment from damage or explosions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] These devices are mainly used in industrial processes where oxy-fuel gas mixtures are handled and used.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] Flashback arrestors as safety products are essential to secure the workplaces and working environment.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] In former times **wet** flashback arrestors were also used.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] Today the industry standard is to use **dry** flashback arrestors with at least two safety elements.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] Dry **flashback arrestors** typically use a combination of safety elements to stop a flashback or reverse flow of gas.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] This type is typically found in cutting and welding applications all over the world.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] They work equally effectively in all orientations, and need very little maintenance.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] The simplest flashback arrestor consists of a metallic tube filled with iron wool, which cools the flame below the ignition temperature.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] In many countries or regions they are mandatory to be installed at the gas regulator or gas outlet/ tapping point.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] Depending on the application they are also often used at the torch side as an additional safety device.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] The flashback arrestors are suitable for most technical gases (fuel gases) such as acetylene, hydrogen, methane, propane, propylene and butane as well as oxygen and compressed air.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] Flashback arrestors have to be tested for gas non-return, for tightness and for gas flow by a qualified person depending on the country specific regulations.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] Liquid seal flame arrestors are liquid barriers following the principle of a siphon where the liquid stops the entering deflagration and/or detonation and extinguishes the flame, they work by bubbling the gas through a non-flammable and ideally non-gas-absorbing liquid, which is typically water.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] They stop the flame by preventing it from reaching the submerged intake.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] These devices are normally very effective at stopping flashbacks from reaching the protected side of the system.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] They have the disadvantages of only working in one orientation and tend to be much larger than dry type arrestors.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] This makes them mainly only suitable for large or fixed installations and the liquid level needs to be constantly checked.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/flashback-arrester] On smaller units having a pressure release valve to prevent the unit from bursting under a severe flashback, the fluid level should be monitored to keep it always above the intake and not so high that the liquid could splash or overflow into the outlet.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] In industrial plants, flare stacks are primarily used for burning off flammable gas released by safety valves during unplanned overpressuring of plant equipment.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] During plant or partial plant startups and shutdowns, they are also often used for the planned combustion of gases over relatively short periods.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] At oil and gas extraction sites, gas flares are similarly used for a variety of startup, maintenance, testing, safety, and emergency purposes.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] In a practice known as production flaring, they may also be used to dispose of large amounts of unwanted associated petroleum gas, possibly throughout the life of an oil well.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] When industrial plant equipment items are overpressured, the pressure relief valve is an essential safety device that automatically releases gases and sometimes liquids.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Those pressure relief valves are required by industrial design codes and standards as well as by law.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] The released gases and liquids are routed through large piping systems called *flare headers* to a vertical elevated flare.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] The released gases are burned as they exit the flare stacks.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] The size and brightness of the resulting flame depends upon the flammable material's flow rate in joules per hour (or btu per hour).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Most industrial plant flares have a vapor–liquid separator (also known as a knockout drum) upstream of the flare to remove any large amounts of liquid that may accompany the relieved gases.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Steam is very often injected into the flame to reduce the formation of black smoke.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] When too much steam is added, a condition known as "oversteaming" can occur resulting in reduced combustion efficiency and higher emissions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] To keep the flare system functional, a small amount of gas is continuously burned, like a pilot light, so that the system is always ready for its primary purpose as an overpressure safety system.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] The height of a flare stack, or the reach of a flare boom, is determined by the thermal radiation that is permissible or tolerable for equipment or personnel to be exposed to.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] For continuous exposure of personnel wearing appropriate industrial clothing a maximum radiation level of 1.58 kW/m2 (500 Btu/hr.ft²) is recommended.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Ground flares are designed to hide the flame from sight and to reduce thermal radiation and noise.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] They comprise a steel box or cylinder lined with refractory material.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] They are open at the top and have openings around the base to allow combustion air to enter.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] They may have an array of multiple flare tips to provide turndown capability and to spread the flame across the cross-section of the flare.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] They are generally used onshore in environmentally sensitive areas and have been used offshore on floating production storage and offloading installations (FPSOs).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] When crude oil is extracted and produced from oil wells, raw natural gas associated with the oil is brought to the surface as well.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Especially in areas of the world lacking pipelines and other gas transportation infrastructure, vast amounts of such associated gas are commonly flared as waste or unusable gas.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] The flaring of associated gas may occur at the top of a vertical flare stack, or it may occur in a ground-level flare in an earthen pit.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Preferably, associated gas is reinjected into the reservoir, which saves it for future use while maintaining higher well pressure and crude oil producibility.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Advances in satellite monitoring, along with voluntary reporting, have revealed that about 150 × 109 cubic meters (5.3 × 1012 cubic feet) of associated gas have been flared globally each year since at least the mid-1990s until 2020.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] In 2011, that was equivalent to about 25 percent of the annual natural gas consumption in the United States or about 30 per cent of the annual gas consumption in the European Union.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] At market, this quantity of gas—at a nominal value of $5.62 per 1000 cubic feet—would be worth US$29.8 billion.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Additionally, the waste is a significant source of carbon dioxide (CO2) and other greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] An important source of anthropogenic methane comes from the treatment and storage of organic waste material including waste water, animal waste and landfill.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Gas flares are used in any process that results in the generation and collection of biogas.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] As a result, gas flares are a standard component of an installation for controlling the production of biogas.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] They are installed on landfill sites, waste water treatment plant and anaerobic digestion plants that use agriculturally or domestically produced organic waste to produce methane for use as a fuel or for heating.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Gas flares on biogas collection systems are used if the gas production rates are not sufficient to warrant use in any industrial process.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] In this latter case, generation of biogas cannot normally be interrupted, and a gas flare is employed to maintain the internal pressure on the biological process.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] There are two types of gas flare used for controlling biogas, open or enclosed.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Flare specification usually demands that enclosed flares must operate at >1000 °C and <1200 °C; this in order to ensure a 98% destruction efficiency and avoid the formation of NOx.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] The natural gas that is not combusted by a flare is vented into the atmosphere as methane.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Methane's estimated global warming potential is 28-36 times greater than that of CO2 over the course of a century, and 84-87 times greater over two decades.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Natural gas flaring produces CO2 and many other compounds, depending on the chemical composition of the natural gas and on how well the natural gas burns in the flare.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Therefore, to the extent that gas flares convert methane to CO2 before it is released into the atmosphere, they reduce the amount of global warming that would otherwise occur.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Flaring emissions contributed to 270 Mt (megatonnes) of CO2 in 2017 and reducing flaring emissions is thought to be an important component in curbing global warming.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] An increasing number of governments and industries have pledged to eliminate or reduce flaring.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] The Global Methane Pledge signed at COP26, in which 111 nations committed to reducing methane emissions by at least 30 percent from 2020 levels by 2030, is also playing a role in raising the global focus on methane.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Additional noxious fumes emitted by flaring may include, aromatic hydrocarbons (benzene, toluene, xylenes) and benzo(a)pyrene, which are known to be carcinogenic.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] A 2013 study found that gas flares contributed over 40% of the black carbon deposited in the Arctic.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Flaring can affect wildlife by attracting birds and insects to the flame.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Approximately 7,500 migrating songbirds were attracted to and killed by the flare at the liquefied natural gas terminal in Saint John, New Brunswick, Canada on September 13, 2013.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Similar incidents have occurred at flares on offshore oil and gas installations.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Moths are known to be attracted to lights.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Over the course of the months and years that the refinery was running a vast number of moths must have been killed, suggesting that plants could not be pollinated over a large area of forest".
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Flares release several different chemicals including: benzene, particulates, nitrogen oxides, heavy metals, black carbon, and carbon monoxide.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Several of these pollutants correlate with preterm birth and reduced newborn birth weight.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] According to one study from 2020, pregnant women living near flaring natural gas and oil wells have reportedly experienced a 50% greater premature birth rate.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] Flares may emit methane and other volatile organic compounds as well as sulfur dioxide and other sulfur compounds, which are known to exacerbate asthma and other respiratory disease.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/gas-flare] A 2021 study found that a 1% increase in flared natural gas increases the respiratory-related hospitalization rate by 0.73%.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The five most abundant greenhouse gases in Earth's atmosphere, listed in decreasing order of average global mole fraction, are: water vapor, carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, ozone.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Other greenhouse gases of concern include chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs and HCFCs), hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs), perfluorocarbons, SF 6, and NF 3.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Water vapor causes about half of the greenhouse effect, acting in response to other gases as a climate change feedback.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Human activities since the beginning of the Industrial Revolution (around 1750) have increased carbon dioxide by over 50%, and methane levels by 150%.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Carbon dioxide emissions are causing about three-quarters of global warming, while methane emissions cause most of the rest.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The vast majority of carbon dioxide emissions by humans come from the burning of fossil fuels, with remaining contributions from agriculture and industry.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Methane emissions originate from agriculture, fossil fuel production, waste, and other sources.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The carbon cycle takes thousands of years to fully absorb CO2 from the atmosphere, while methane lasts in the atmosphere for an average of only 12 years.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Natural flows of carbon happen between the atmosphere, terrestrial ecosystems, the ocean, and sediments.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] These flows have been fairly balanced over the past one million years, although greenhouse gas levels have varied widely in the more distant past.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Carbon dioxide levels are now higher than they have been for three million years.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The 2023 annual update of key indicators reveals that human-induced temperature rise, greenhouse gas concentrations, and the Earth's energy imbalance have all reached new records.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] If current emission rates continue, then global warming will surpass 2.0 °C (3.6 °F) sometime between 2040 and 2070.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] This is a level which the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) says is "dangerous".
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Greenhouse gases are infrared active, meaning that they absorb and emit infrared radiation in the same long wavelength range as what is emitted by the Earth's surface, clouds and atmosphere.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] 99% of the Earth's dry atmosphere (excluding water vapor) is made up of nitrogen (N 2) (78%) and oxygen (O 2) (21%).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Because their molecules contain two atoms of the same element, they have no asymmetry in the distribution of their electrical charges, and so are almost totally unaffected by infrared thermal radiation, with only an extremely minor effect from collision-induced absorption.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] A further 0.9% of the atmosphere is made up by argon (Ar), which is monatomic, and so completely transparent to thermal radiation.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] This makes them infrared active, and so their presence causes greenhouse effect.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Earth absorbs some of the radiant energy received from the sun, reflects some of it as light, and reflects or radiates the rest back to space as heat.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] A planet's surface temperature depends on this balance between incoming and outgoing energy.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] When Earth's energy balance is shifted, its surface becomes warmer or cooler, leading to a variety of changes in global climate.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] *Radiative forcing* is a metric calculated in watts per square meter, which characterizes the impact of an external change in a factor that influences climate.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] It is calculated as the difference in top-of-atmosphere (TOA) energy balance immediately caused by such an external change.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] A positive forcing, such as from increased concentrations of greenhouse gases, means more energy arriving than leaving at the top-of-atmosphere, which causes additional warming, while negative forcing, like from sulfates forming in the atmosphere from sulfur dioxide, leads to cooling.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Within the lower atmosphere, greenhouse gases exchange thermal radiation with the surface and limit radiative heat flow away from it, which reduces the overall rate of upward radiative heat transfer.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The increased concentration of greenhouse gases is also cooling the upper atmosphere, as it is much thinner than the lower layers, and any heat re-emitted from greenhouse gases is more likely to travel further to space than to interact with the fewer gas molecules in the upper layers.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The upper atmosphere is also shrinking as the result.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Anthropogenic changes to the natural greenhouse effect are sometimes referred to as the *enhanced greenhouse effect*.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] This table shows the most important contributions to the overall greenhouse effect, without which the average temperature of Earth's surface would be about −18 °C (0 °F), instead of around 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] This table also specifies *tropospheric* ozone, because this gas has a cooling effect in the stratosphere, but a warming influence comparable to nitrous oxide and CFCs in the troposphere.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Water vapor is the most important greenhouse gas overall, being responsible for 41–67% of the greenhouse effect, but its global concentrations are not directly affected by human activity.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] While local water vapor concentrations can be affected by developments such as irrigation, it has little impact on the global scale due to its short residence time of about nine days.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Indirectly, an increase in global temperatures will also increase water vapor concentrations and thus their warming effect, in a process known as water vapor feedback.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] It occurs because the Clausius–Clapeyron relation holds that more water vapor will be present per unit volume at elevated temperatures.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Thus, local atmospheric concentration of water vapor varies from less than 0.01% in extremely cold regions up to 3% by mass in saturated air at about 32 °C.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Global warming potential (GWP) is a measure of how much heat a greenhouse gas (GHG) traps in the atmosphere over a specific time period, relative to carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] It is a dimensionless quantity expressed as a multiple of warming caused by the same mass of CO2.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Therefore, by definition CO2 has a GWP of 1.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] For other gases, it depends on how strongly the gas absorbs thermal radiation, how quickly it leaves the atmosphere, and the time frame considered.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] For example, methane (CH4) has a GWP over 20 years (GWP-20) of 81.2 meaning that, a leak of a tonne of methane is equivalent to emitting 81.2 tonnes of CO2, both measured over 20 years.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] As methane has a much shorter atmospheric lifetime than CO2, its GWP is much less over longer time periods, with a GWP-100 of 27.9 and a GWP-500 of 7.95.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Greenhouse gas emissions (GHG emissions) can be expressed in terms of carbon dioxide equivalent mass or just carbon dioxide equivalent (symbolized CO2e or CO2eq, also denoted CO2-e or CO2-eq) can be calculated from the GWP and emitted mass.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] For any gas, it is the mass of CO2 that would warm the earth as much as the mass of that gas.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Thus it provides a common scale for measuring the climate effects of different gases.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] It is calculated as GWP times mass of the other gas; it is typically expressed in gigatonnes (symbol Gt).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The contribution of each gas to the enhanced greenhouse effect is determined by the characteristics of that gas, its abundance, and any indirect effects it may cause.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] For example, the direct radiative effect of a mass of methane is about 84 times stronger than the same mass of carbon dioxide over a 20-year time frame.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Since the 1980s, greenhouse gas forcing contributions (relative to year 1750) are also estimated with high accuracy using IPCC-recommended expressions derived from radiative transfer models.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The concentration of a greenhouse gas is typically measured in *parts per million* (ppm) or *parts per billion* (ppb) by volume.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] A CO2 concentration of 420 ppm means that 420 out of every million air molecules is a CO2 molecule.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The first 30 ppm increase in CO2 concentrations took place in about 200 years, from the start of the Industrial Revolution to 1958; however the next 90 ppm increase took place within 56 years, from 1958 to 2014.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Similarly, the average annual increase in the 1960s was only 37% of what it was in 2000 through 2007.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Many observations are available online in a variety of Atmospheric Chemistry Observational Databases.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The table below shows the most influential long-lived, well-mixed greenhouse gases, along with their tropospheric concentrations and direct radiative forcings, as identified by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Abundances of these trace gases are regularly measured by atmospheric scientists from samples collected throughout the world.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] It excludes water vapor because changes in its concentrations are calculated as a climate change feedback indirectly caused by changes in other greenhouse gases, as well as ozone, whose concentrations are only modified indirectly by various refrigerants that cause ozone depletion.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The abbreviations TAR, AR4, AR5 and AR6 refer to the different IPCC reports over the years.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The baseline is pre-industrialization (year 1750).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] AR6 reports the *effective radiative forcing* which includes effects of rapid adjustments in the atmosphere and at the surface.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The IPCC states that *"no single atmospheric lifetime can be given"* for CO2.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] This is mostly due to the rapid growth and cumulative magnitude of the disturbances to Earth's carbon cycle by the geologic extraction and burning of fossil carbon.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] As of year 2014, fossil CO2 emitted as a theoretical 10 to 100 GtC pulse on top of the existing atmospheric concentration was expected to be 50% removed by land vegetation and ocean sinks in less than about a century, as based on the projections of coupled models referenced in the AR5 assessment.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] A substantial fraction (20–35%) was also projected to remain in the atmosphere for centuries to millennia, where fractional persistence increases with pulse size.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Figure is combined total natural abundance of all perfluorocarbons: no data exist for individual compounds.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Atmospheric concentrations are determined by the balance between sources (emissions of the gas from human activities and natural systems) and sinks (the removal of the gas from the atmosphere by conversion to a different chemical compound or absorption by bodies of water).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The proportion of an emission remaining in the atmosphere after a specified time is the "airborne fraction" (AF).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The *annual airborne fraction* is the ratio of the atmospheric increase in a given year to that year's total emissions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The annual airborne fraction for CO2 had been stable at 0.45 for the past six decades even as the emissions have been increasing.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] This means that the other 0.55 of emitted CO2 is absorbed by the land and atmosphere carbon sinks within the first year of an emission.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] In the high-emission scenarios, the effectiveness of carbon sinks will be lower, increasing the atmospheric fraction of CO2 even though the raw amount of emissions absorbed will be higher than in the present.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Major greenhouse gases are well mixed and take many years to leave the atmosphere.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The atmospheric lifetime of a greenhouse gas refers to the time required to restore equilibrium following a sudden increase or decrease in its concentration in the atmosphere.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Individual atoms or molecules may be lost or deposited to sinks such as the soil, the oceans and other waters, or vegetation and other biological systems, reducing the excess to background concentrations.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The average time taken to achieve this is the mean lifetime.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] This can be represented through the following formula, where the lifetime $\tau$ of an atmospheric species X in a one-box model is the average time that a molecule of X remains in the box.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] If input of this gas into the box ceased, then after time $\tau$ , its concentration would decrease by about 63%.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Changes to any of these variables can alter the atmospheric lifetime of a greenhouse gas.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] For instance, methane's atmospheric lifetime is estimated to have been lower in the 19th century than now, but to have been higher in the second half of the 20th century than after 2000.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Carbon dioxide has an even more variable lifetime, which cannot be specified down to a single number.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Scientists instead say that while the first 10% of carbon dioxide's airborne fraction (not counting the ~50% absorbed by land and ocean sinks within the emission's first year) is removed "quickly", the vast majority of the airborne fraction – 80% – lasts for "centuries to millennia".
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The remaining 10% stays for tens of thousands of years.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] In some models, this longest-lasting fraction is as large as 30%.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Estimates in 2023 found that the current carbon dioxide concentration in the atmosphere may be the highest it has been in the last 14 million years.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] However the IPCC Sixth Assessment Report estimated similar levels 3 to 3.3 million years ago in the mid-Pliocene warm period.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] This period can be a proxy for likely climate outcomes with current levels of CO2.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Carbon dioxide is believed to have played an important effect in regulating Earth's temperature throughout its 4.54 billion year history.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Early in the Earth's life, scientists have found evidence of liquid water indicating a warm world even though the Sun's output is believed to have only been 70% of what it is today.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Higher carbon dioxide concentrations in the early Earth's atmosphere might help explain this faint young sun paradox.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] When Earth first formed, Earth's atmosphere may have contained more greenhouse gases and CO2 concentrations may have been higher, with estimated partial pressure as large as 1,000 kPa (10 bar), because there was no bacterial photosynthesis to reduce the gas to carbon compounds and oxygen.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Methane, a very active greenhouse gas, may have been more prevalent as well.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Greenhouse gas monitoring involves the direct measurement of atmospheric concentrations and direct and indirect measurement of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Indirect methods calculate emissions of greenhouse gases based on related metrics such as fossil fuel extraction.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] There are several different methods of measuring carbon dioxide concentrations in the atmosphere, including infrared analyzing and manometry.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Methane and nitrous oxide are measured by other instruments, such as the range-resolved infrared differential absorption lidar (DIAL).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Greenhouse gases are measured from space such as by the Orbiting Carbon Observatory and through networks of ground stations such as the Integrated Carbon Observation System.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The Annual Greenhouse Gas Index (AGGI) is defined by atmospheric scientists at NOAA as the ratio of total direct radiative forcing due to long-lived and well-mixed greenhouse gases for any year for which adequate global measurements exist, to that present in year 1990.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] These radiative forcing levels are relative to those present in year 1750 (i.e. prior to the start of the industrial era).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] 1990 is chosen because it is the baseline year for the Kyoto Protocol, and is the publication year of the first IPCC Scientific Assessment of Climate Change.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] As such, NOAA states that the AGGI "measures the commitment that (global) society has already made to living in a changing climate.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] It is based on the highest quality atmospheric observations from sites around the world.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] There are several surface measurement (including flasks and continuous in situ) networks including NOAA/ERSL, WDCGG, and RAMCES.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The NOAA/ESRL Baseline Observatory Network, and the Scripps Institution of Oceanography Network data are hosted at the CDIAC at ORNL.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The World Data Centre for Greenhouse Gases (WDCGG), part of GAW, data are hosted by the JMA.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The Reseau Atmospherique de Mesure des Composes an Effet de Serre database (RAMCES) is part of IPSL.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The natural flows of carbon between the atmosphere, ocean, terrestrial ecosystems, and sediments are fairly balanced; so carbon levels would be roughly stable without human influence.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Carbon dioxide is removed from the atmosphere primarily through photosynthesis and enters the terrestrial and oceanic biospheres.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Carbon dioxide also dissolves directly from the atmosphere into bodies of water (ocean, lakes, etc.), as well as dissolving in precipitation as raindrops fall through the atmosphere.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] When dissolved in water, carbon dioxide reacts with water molecules and forms carbonic acid.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] It can then acidify the surfaces it touches, thereby be absorbed by rocks through weathering, or be washed into the ocean contributing to ocean acidity.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The atmospheric carbon cycle accounts for the exchange of gaseous carbon compounds, primarily carbon dioxide (CO2), between Earth's atmosphere, the oceans, and the terrestrial biosphere.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] It is one of the faster components of the planet's overall carbon cycle, supporting the exchange of more than 200 billion tons of carbon (i.e. gigatons carbon or GtC) in and out of the atmosphere throughout the course of each year.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Atmospheric concentrations of CO2 remain stable over longer timescales only when there exists a balance between these two flows.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Methane (CH4), Carbon monoxide (CO), and other human-made compounds are present in smaller concentrations and are also part of the atmospheric carbon cycle.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The vast majority of carbon dioxide emissions by humans come from the burning of fossil fuels.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Additional contributions come from cement manufacturing, fertilizer production, and changes in land use like deforestation.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Rice paddies are a significant agricultural source of greenhouse gas emissions, contributing 22% of total agricultural methane and 11% of nitrous oxide emissions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] If current emission rates continue then temperature rises will surpass 2.0 °C (3.6 °F) sometime between 2040 and 2070, which is the level the United Nations' Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) says is "dangerous".
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Most greenhouse gases have both natural and human-caused sources.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] An exception are purely human-produced synthetic halocarbons which have no natural sources.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] During the pre-industrial Holocene, concentrations of existing gases were roughly constant, because the large natural sources and sinks roughly balanced.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] In the industrial era, human activities have added greenhouse gases to the atmosphere, mainly through the burning of fossil fuels and clearing of forests.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Though the greenhouse effect is heavily driven by water vapor, human emissions of water vapor are not a significant contributor to warming.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The annual "Emissions Gap Report" by UNEP stated in 2022 that it was necessary to almost halve emissions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] In 2022, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) released its Sixth Assessment Report on climate change.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] It warned that greenhouse gas emissions must peak before 2025 at the latest and decline 43% by 2030 to have a good chance of limiting global warming to 1.5 °C (2.7 °F).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Or in the words of Secretary-General of the United Nations António Guterres: "Main emitters must drastically cut emissions starting this year".
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] According to a joint press release published by the German Physical society and the German meteorological society in September 2025, if the current trends will continue, global temperature can rise to 3°C above pre-industrial level by the year 2050, and by 5°C by the year 2100.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The scientists emphasised the need to urgently implement already existing solutions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Several technologies remove greenhouse gas emissions from the atmosphere.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Most widely analyzed are those that remove carbon dioxide from the atmosphere, either to geologic formations such as bio-energy with carbon capture and storage and carbon dioxide air capture, or to the soil as in the case with biochar.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Many long-term climate scenario models require large-scale human-made negative emissions to avoid serious climate change.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Negative emissions approaches are also being studied for atmospheric methane, called atmospheric methane removal.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] In the early 20th century, researchers realized that greenhouse gases in the atmosphere made Earth's overall temperature higher than it would be without them.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] The term *greenhouse* was first applied to this phenomenon by Nils Gustaf Ekholm in 1901.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] During the late 20th century, a scientific consensus evolved that increasing concentrations of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere cause a substantial rise in global temperatures and changes to other parts of the climate system, with consequences for the environment and for human health.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/greenhouse-gas] Greenhouse gases exist in many atmospheres, creating greenhouse effects on Mars, Titan, and particularly in the thick atmosphere of Venus.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] In organic chemistry, a **hydrocarbon** is an organic compound consisting entirely of hydrogen and carbon.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Hydrocarbons are examples of group 14 hydrides.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Hydrocarbons are generally colourless and hydrophobic; their odor is usually faint, and may be similar to that of gasoline or lighter fluid.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] They occur in a diverse range of molecular structures and phases: they can be gases (such as methane and propane), liquids (such as hexane and benzene), low melting solids (such as paraffin wax and naphthalene) or polymers (such as polyethylene and polystyrene).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] In the fossil fuel industries, *hydrocarbon* refers to naturally occurring petroleum, natural gas and coal, or their hydrocarbon derivatives and purified forms.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Combustion of hydrocarbons is the main source of the world's energy.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Petroleum is the dominant raw-material source for organic commodity chemicals such as solvents and polymers.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Most anthropogenic (human-generated) emissions of greenhouse gases are either carbon dioxide released by the burning of fossil fuels, or methane released from the handling of natural gas or from agriculture.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Unsaturated hydrocarbons, which have one or more double or triple bonds between carbon atoms.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Those with one or more double bonds are called alkenes.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Those with one double bond have the formula C*n*H2*n* (assuming non-cyclic structures).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Those containing triple bonds are called alkyne.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Those with one triple bond have the formula C*n*H2*n*−2.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Aromatic hydrocarbons, also known as arenes, which are hydrocarbons that have at least one aromatic ring.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] 10% of total nonmethane organic carbon emission are aromatic hydrocarbons from the exhaust of gasoline-powered vehicles.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] The term 'aliphatic' refers to non-aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Saturated aliphatic hydrocarbons are sometimes referred to as 'paraffins'.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Aliphatic hydrocarbons containing a double bond between carbon atoms are sometimes referred to as 'olefins'.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] The predominant use of hydrocarbons is as a combustible fuel source.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Methane is the predominant component of natural gas.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] C6 through C10 alkanes, alkenes, cycloalkanes, and aromatic hydrocarbons are the main components of gasoline, naphtha, jet fuel, and specialized industrial solvent mixtures.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] With the progressive addition of carbon units, the simple non-ring structured hydrocarbons have higher viscosities, lubricating indices, boiling points, and solidification temperatures.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] At the opposite extreme from methane lie the heavy tars that remain as the *lowest fraction* in a crude oil refining retort.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] They are collected and widely utilized as roofing compounds, pavement material (bitumen), wood preservatives (the creosote series) and as extremely high viscosity shear-resisting liquids.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Some large-scale non-fuel applications of hydrocarbons begin with ethane and propane, which are obtained from petroleum and natural gas.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] These two gases are converted either to syngas or to ethylene and propylene respectively.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Global consumption of benzene in 2021 is estimated at more than 58 million metric tons, which will increase to 60 million tons in 2022.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Hydrocarbons are also prevalent in nature.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Some eusocial arthropods, such as the Brazilian stingless bee, *Schwarziana quadripunctata*, use unique cuticular hydrocarbon "scents" in order to determine kin from non-kin.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] This hydrocarbon composition varies between age, sex, nest location, and hierarchal position.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] There is also potential to harvest hydrocarbons from plants like *Euphorbia lathyris* and *E. tirucalli* as an alternative and renewable energy source for vehicles that use diesel.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Furthermore, endophytic bacteria from plants that naturally produce hydrocarbons have been used in hydrocarbon degradation in attempts to deplete hydrocarbon concentration in polluted soils.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Saturated hydrocarbons are notable for their inertness.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Unsaturated hydrocarbons (alkenes, alkynes and aromatic compounds) react more readily, by means of substitution, addition, polymerization.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] At higher temperatures they undergo dehydrogenation, oxidation and combustion.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] The cracking of saturated hydrocarbons is the main industrial route to alkenes and alkyne.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] These reactions require heterogeneous catalysts and temperatures >500 °C.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Oxidation of hydrocarbons involves their reaction with oxygen.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] In the presence of excess oxygen, hydrocarbons combust.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] With careful conditions, which have been optimized for many years, partial oxidation results.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Useful compounds can be obtained in this way: maleic acid from butane, terephthalic acid from xylenes, acetone together with phenol from cumene (isopropylbenzene), and cyclohexanone from cyclohexane.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] The process, which is called autoxidation, begins with the formation of hydroperoxides (ROOH).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Combustion of hydrocarbons is currently the main source of the world's energy for electric power generation, heating (such as home heating), and transportation.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Often this energy is used directly as heat such as in home heaters, which use either petroleum or natural gas.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] The hydrocarbon is burnt and the heat is used to heat water, which is then circulated.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] A similar principle is used to create electrical energy in power plants.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Both saturated and unsaturated hydrocarbons undergo this process.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Common properties of hydrocarbons are the facts that they produce steam, carbon dioxide and heat during combustion and that oxygen is required for combustion to take place.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Partial oxidation characterizes the reactions of alkenes and oxygen.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] This process is the basis of rancidification and paint drying.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Saturated hydrocarbons react with chlorine and fluorine.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] In the case of chlorination, one of the chlorine atoms replaces a hydrogen atom.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] The reactions proceed via free-radical pathways, in which the halogen first dissociates into two neutral radical atoms (homolytic fission).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Aromatic compounds, almost uniquely for hydrocarbons, undergo substitution reactions.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] The resulting ethylbenzene is dehydrogenated to styrene and then polymerized to manufacture polystyrene, a common thermoplastic material.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Addition reactions apply to alkenes and alkynes.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] It is because they add reagents that they are called unsaturated.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] In this reaction a variety of reagents add "across" the pi-bond(s).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Chlorine, hydrogen chloride, water, and hydrogen are illustrative reagents.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Alkenes and some alkynes undergo polymerization by opening of the multiple bonds to produce polyethylene, polybutylene, and polystyrene.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] The alkyne acetylene polymerizes to produce polyacetylene.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Oligomers (chains of a few monomers) may be produced, for example in the Shell higher olefin process, where α-olefins are extended to make longer α-olefins by adding ethylene repeatedly.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Some hydrocarbons undergo *metathesis*, in which substituents attached by C–C bonds are exchanged between molecules.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] For a single C–C bond it is alkane metathesis, for a double C–C bond it is alkene metathesis (olefin metathesis), and for a triple C–C bond it is alkyne metathesis.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] The vast majority of hydrocarbons found on Earth occur in crude oil, petroleum, coal, and natural gas.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] For thousands of years they have been exploited and used for a vast range of purposes.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] 'rock oil') and coal are generally thought to be products of decomposition of organic matter.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Coal, in contrast to petroleum, is richer in carbon and poorer in hydrogen.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Natural gas is the product of methanogenesis.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] A seemingly limitless variety of compounds comprise petroleum, hence the necessity of refineries.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] These hydrocarbons consist of saturated hydrocarbons, aromatic hydrocarbons, or combinations of the two.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Missing in petroleum are alkenes and alkynes.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Petroleum-derived hydrocarbons are mainly consumed for fuel, but they are also the source of virtually all synthetic organic compounds, including plastics and pharmaceuticals.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Natural gas is consumed almost exclusively as fuel.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Coal is used as a fuel and as a reducing agent in metallurgy.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] A small fraction of hydrocarbon found on earth, and all currently known hydrocarbon found on other planets and moons, is thought to be abiological.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Hydrocarbons such as ethylene, isoprene, and monoterpenes are emitted by living vegetation.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Some hydrocarbons also are widespread and abundant in the Solar System.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Lakes of liquid methane and ethane have been found on Titan, Saturn's largest moon, as confirmed by the *Cassini–Huygens* space probe.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Hydrocarbons are also abundant in nebulae forming polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon compounds.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Burning hydrocarbons as fuel, which produces carbon dioxide and water, is a major contributor to anthropogenic global warming.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Hydrocarbons are introduced into the environment through their extensive use as fuels and chemicals as well as through leaks or accidental spills during exploration, production, refining, or transport of fossil fuels.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Anthropogenic hydrocarbon contamination of soil is a serious global issue due to contaminant persistence and the negative impact on human health.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] When soil is contaminated by hydrocarbons, it can have a significant impact on its microbiological, chemical, and physical properties.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] This can serve to prevent, slow down or even accelerate the growth of vegetation depending on the exact changes that occur.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Crude oil and natural gas are the two largest sources of hydrocarbon contamination of soil.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Bioremediation of hydrocarbon from soil or water contaminated is a formidable challenge because of the chemical inertness that characterize hydrocarbons (hence they survived millions of years in the source rock).
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Nonetheless, many strategies have been devised, bioremediation being prominent.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] The basic problem with bioremediation is the paucity of enzymes that act on them.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Nonetheless, the area has received regular attention.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Bacteria in the gabbroic layer of the ocean's crust can degrade hydrocarbons; but the extreme environment makes research difficult.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Other bacteria such as *Lutibacterium anuloederans* can also degrade hydrocarbons.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Mycoremediation or breaking down of hydrocarbon by mycelium and mushrooms is possible.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Hydrocarbons are generally of low toxicity, hence the widespread use of gasoline and related volatile products.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Aromatic compounds such as benzene and toluene are narcotic and chronic toxins, and benzene in particular is known to be carcinogenic.
[src:detonation-flame-arrester/hydrocarbon] Certain rare polycyclic aromatic compounds are carcinogenic.
